Now languages, as a matter of choice, are valued as highly as science-technology-engineering and mathematics group subjects in independent school programs.
A 2014 survey by the Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of employers cited a lack of language skills as a reason for failing to fill vacancies.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming compulsory to prepare young people for their future careers.
As job opportunities increase, which will require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of their chosen career, learning a foreign language will bring them a real advantage in the future from such long-term skills.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically improve the competitiveness of a multi-lingual speaker.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in Britain, 75 percent did not know a foreign language well enough to maintain conversation, while French was the only one spoken by a double-digit number of people, 15 percent.
