Harvard University students will learn a subject about how to relax enough
A new subject at Harvard University this year has resulted in students sleeping more, and it is an attempt to counter the increasingly popular culture of brutalism, which includes caffeine crowded study through the nights.
One teacher found that students at the best university in the world often do not even have basic knowledge of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, as well as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a subject he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
Inspiration to create a new subject for him arose after speaking about the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came up to me and asked, "Why is it telling me only now that I'm in the last course?"
She discovered that no one had ever explained to her the importance of sleep — which surprised me, he told the Telegraph.
This year, the first study subject released provides students with basic information on how good sleep habits contribute to achievement in learning and sport, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, informed that the university decided to introduce a course of instruction after learning that students were suffering from serious sleep deprivation during the school week.
The hour-long training process includes a series of interactive tasks.
One of the parts features a dormitory door picture where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books to learn about caffeine and light exposure and how performance in sports is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another part, students are informed about how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Then the campus map with interactive icons invites participants to rethink their daily routine.
"We know that this will not change student behavior immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know. Just as you have the right to know how health will be affected by cigarette smoking," added Professor Chaisler.
He said that the culture of being proud of the ability to learn throughout the night still exists, and he added that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation became an increasingly serious problem.
He explained that providing enough quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, overwork and anxiety, and even to prevent weight gain as lack of sleep switches the brain into fasting mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler develop a subject, after taking part in one of the professor's lectures last year, Harvard's first course.
He said the subject had opened his eyes and inspired the course to be accessible to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be a request for postgraduate students to learn a similar program before going on to enjoy competition.
Professor Chaisler advises students to install an alarm clock not only for the time they rise, but also when they go to sleep, as well as to keep in mind how people are harmed by "blue lights" emitted by electronic device screens and LED lamps, as they can disrupt circadian rhythms, making it difficult to sleep.
