The National Trust listens to the lives of secret batsmen
The new study, which is being conducted at a Scottish Highland estate, focuses on discovering how batsmen use the landscape in the food search process.
The findings are expected to bring new clarity to the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help in their protection measures in the future.
Scientists at the Scottish National Trust in Invereve Gardens in Westeros will study dwarf bats, pygmy bats, as well as brown long-eared and water night bats.
In key locations, special recorders will be placed on the property, which will track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand detectors.
Sound experts will analyze all records to determine the frequency of bat calls and which species perform the particular activities.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed landscape view reflecting the behavior of bats.
NTS conservation adviser Rob Dewar hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management works such as the creation of meadows and how best to conserve forests for bats and other associated species.
During the last centenary, the bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined significantly.
These lands are threatened by construction and development work affecting the hideout and loss of residence of batsmen.
Wind generators and lighting can also pose risks, as can flypaper and chemical treatments of some building materials, as well as cat attacks.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes during hunting.
They use a sophisticated echo-location method to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for maintaining more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the bat problem very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, checks on bat hideouts, and sometimes even rescues.
The organization has even established in Scotland the first and only specially designed reserve for bats on the property of "Threave" in Damfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten bat species found in Scotland reside.
The property manager, David Thompson, claims that the area is ideal for bats.
"Here's a great place for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees and generally suitable habitat.
But there are still many things we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand better what they need for survival."
He stressed that it was important to check whether bats would not be housed at the site before carrying out maintenance work on the property, as it may occur that hiding places of one female are killed by unintentional destruction of up to 400 females and their young, thus possibly destroying the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and must not be killed, tormented, disturbed or destroyed by their hideouts.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a member of the Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and for a number of their species we just don't know how they're doing."
