Latest news on red tide: Concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Committee (FWC) points to a general decrease in red tide concentrations for part of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, flowering spots have been reported in Pinela, Manatí, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier — suggesting a decrease in concentration.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles from North Pinella to the sea shoreline of the Southern Lee area.
The spots can be found about 10 miles from the maritime coastal zone of Hillsborough County, but in some places take about a week.
The red tide has also been cleared in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations in Pinela County or its maritime coastal zone, low to high concentrations in the maritime coastal zone of Hilsboro County, low to high concentrations in Manatí County, low to high concentrations in the Sarasota County or its maritime coastal zone, low to moderate concentrations in the Charlotte County, low to high concentrations in the Lee County or its maritime coastal zone, and low concentrations in the Collier County have been reported.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in the Pinela, Manatí, Sarasota, Lee and Collier areas.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in Northwest Florida last week.
